## TypeScript Standards

### Strict Mode

**Configuration:** TypeScript strict mode is implicitly enabled via tsconfig.json

```typescript
// ✅ Always provide explicit types
interface ButtonProps {
  variant?: "primary" | "secondary";
  size?: "sm" | "md" | "lg";
  children: React.ReactNode;
}

// ❌ Avoid 'any' type
const data: any = fetchData(); // Bad

// ✅ Use proper typing
const data: User[] = fetchData(); // Good
```

### Type Annotations

**Component Props:**

```typescript
// ✅ Use interfaces for props
interface HeaderProps {
  title: string;
  isSticky?: boolean; // Optional with ?
}

export const Header: React.FC<HeaderProps> = ({ title, isSticky = true }) => {
  // ...
};
```

**Extending Native Types:**

```typescript
// ✅ Extend HTML element types
interface ButtonProps extends React.ButtonHTMLAttributes<HTMLButtonElement> {
  variant?: "primary" | "outline";
}

// This gives you onClick, disabled, etc. automatically
```

**State Typing:**

```typescript
// ✅ TypeScript can infer simple state
const [isOpen, setIsOpen] = useState(false);

// ✅ Explicit typing for complex state
const [user, setUser] = useState<User | null>(null);
```

### Type Organization

**Current Pattern:** Types are defined inline near usage

```typescript
// ✅ Interface above component
interface CardProps {
  title: string;
}

const Card: React.FC<CardProps> = ({ title }) => {
  /* ... */
};
```

**Future:** When types are shared across 3+ files, extract to `/types/` directory

